message.content:
The images provided display forms with information on gravestone inscriptions from a graveyard survey with the following details for each entry:

1. **Image 1 (Top Half)**
   - Graveyard Name: OLCN'S Mtown Churchyard
   - Inscription: 
     Erected by 
     John Britt 
     In Memory of his Wife
     Ellen Britt
     who died April 14, 1886
     Aged 26 years
     ----
     The above
     John Britt Ric
     Died Feb. 25, 1889
     Aged 44 years
     R I P
   - Memorial Number: 9

   **(Bottom Half)**
   - Graveyard Name: (Unfilled)
   - Inscription:
     Kerbing only -
     No headstone remaining
   - Memorial Number: 10

2. **Image 2 (Top Half)**
   - Graveyard Name: ICWS
   - Inscription:
     Walls
     9' x 9' square
     No inscription
   - Memorial Number: 88

   **(Bottom Half)**
   - Graveyard Name: ICWO
   - Inscription:
     Erected by
     Lawrence Burke
     of Ploughristin
     in memory of his
     father & mother &
     brother
   - Memorial Number: 89

3. **Image 3 (Top Half)**
   - Graveyard Name: OLCWS (There is a notation which seems to say: MT TOWERS 9/10/20)
   - Inscription:
     Bran'sfield 1941
     Sacred to the memory of
     Mary Relic of the Late Michael
     Fitzgerald of Atwood in the County
     of Limerick Esq. who departed this
     life at Mickleston on the 21st day
     of March 1848 in the 70th year of
     his Age
   - Memorial Number: 104
   - Additional Note: The checkbox next to "Chest tomb" is marked.

   **(Bottom Half)**
   - Graveyard Name: (Unfilled)
   - Inscription:
     Bran'sfield
     In loving Richard and
     Mary Evans &
     now family
     Also
     Ann & Kate
     R I P
   - Memorial Number: 105

The forms also contain checkboxes for different types of grave markers and materials, but not all checkboxes are marked. Each entry includes a hand-drawn sketch of the gravestone shape. The sketches show varying designs, such as a traditional headstone and a chest tomb.
